  "prompt": "What are the differences between pastrami, corned beef, roast beef and Canadians' \"smoked meat?\"",
  "response": "Here's a breakdown of these meat types:\n\n1. Pastrami:\n- Made from beef brisket\n- Heavily seasoned with black pepper, coriander, and other spices\n- Cured, then smoked\n- Typically served hot, sliced thin\n- Associated with Jewish deli cuisine\n\n2. Corned Beef:\n- Made from beef brisket or round\n- Cured in large grains of rock salt (called \"corns\")\n- Boiled or slow-cooked\n- Often associated with Irish cuisine\n- Commonly served on St. Patrick's Day\n\n3. Roast Beef:\n- Prepared by roasting a cut of beef in an oven\n- Typically seasoned simply with salt and pepper\n- Served hot or cold\n- Can be sliced thin or thick\n- Often used in sandwiches\n\n4. Montreal Smoked Meat (Canadian):\n- Similar to pastrami\n- Made from beef brisket\n- Cured with different spices than pastrami\n- Longer curing and smoking process\n- Typically sliced thicker than pastrami\n- Iconic in Montreal's culinary tradition\n\nEach has distinct preparation methods, flavors, and cultural origins.",
